State MSM Profile: Illinois

Background & Methods

In 2015-2016, researchers at Emory University partnered with colleagues at the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) to develop methods to estimate the number of men who have sex with men (MSM) residing in each county in the United States. Using population and housing data from the American Community Survey and estimates from two peer-reviewed publications (Oster et al., 2015 & Purcell et al., 2012), they derived an indirect estimate of MSM population sizes that took into account both the urbanicity of the county as well as its density of households with a male householder and a male same-sex partner.

The full methodology is published in the Journal of Medical Internet Research - Public Health and Surveillance:

Grey JA, Bernstein KT, Sullivan PS, Purcell DW, Chesson HW, Gift TL, Rosenberg ES. Estimating the population sizes of men who have sex with men in US states and counties using data from the American Community Survey. JMIR Public Health Surveill 2016;2(1):e14. DOI: 10.2196/publichealth.5365

Overview of MSM in Illinois

An estimated 199,486 men who have sex with men (MSM) resided in Illinois in 2013, representing 4.4% of the 4,503,084 MSM in the United States. Of the 4,728,089 adult men of Illinois, 4.2% had had sex with another man in the past 5 years, which was greater than the overall percentage of adult men in the United States who were MSM (3.9%).

Most MSM in Illinois resided in central counties of large metropolitan areas (63.1%). Including both central and fringe counties, 86.8% resided in a large metropolitan area.


Percentage of MSM by urbanicity, United States and Illinois, 2013

MSM in Illinois Counties

Among counties or county-equivalent areas in Illinois, Cook County had the largest population of MSM at 125,923, representing 63.1% of all MSM in the state. Cook County also had the highest percentage of MSM among adult men in Illinois at 6.6%. This was greater than the percentage for Illinois as a whole, which was 4.2% of adult men.

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.



MSM in Illinois Metropolitan Statistical Areas

Chicago-Naperville-Elgin Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Chicago-Naperville-Elgin MSA overlaps three states: Illinois, Indiana and Wisconsin. The Illinois portion of the MSA had the largest metropolitan population of MSM in Illinois at 165,226, or 82.8% of all MSM in the state and 94.4% of the 175,118 MSM in the MSA. Of the 3,128,720 adult men in the Illinois part of Chicago-Naperville-Elgin, an estimated 5.3% were MSM. This was greater than the percentage of MSM among adult men in the MSA as a whole, which was 5.1% of adult men (175,118 out of 3,443,489).



Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.




St. Louis Metropolitan Statistical Area

The St. Louis MSA overlaps two states: Illinois and Missouri. The Illinois portion of the MSA had 7,985 MSM, or 4.0% of all MSM in the state and 20.9% of the 38,221 MSM in the MSA. Of 257,783 adult men in the Illinois part of St. Louis, 3.1% were MSM. This was less than the overall percentage of MSM among adult men in the MSA, which was 3.8% of adult men (38,221 out of 1,015,361).

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.
